text: The simultaneous maximum-likelihood-estimation procedures are used to examine the hypothesized relationships among total quality management, market orientation and hotel performance. Figure shows the path coefficients for the model and their significance. Regarding the hypothesis tests, all of the hypothesized relationships are supported for the estimated structural model. Total quality management significantly and positively affects both hotel performance (0.446, 8.581) and market orientation (0.388, 7.343). Furthermore, market orientation also significantly and positively affects hotel performance (0.269, 4.906). These results reveal that market orientation mediates the influence on hotel performance.

The establishes a strong relation between positive attitudes towards science and technology and perceived benefits of science and technology. The same happens, this group shows a positive relation between perceived benefits of science and technology and positive attitudes towards biotechnology. It shows the same sign and level of significance as other groups, but the path coefficient is lower. In conclusion, older people understand benefits of science and technology differently than the rest of respondents, especially regarding its relation towards the environment. However, the behavioral process that goes from science and technology benefit perception to GM food benefit perception is similar for the entire sample no matter the age of respondents.

In figure, a significant correlation of -.65 between Hick g and temporal g was observed. With the correlation among predictors controlled, temporal g remained a highly significant independent predictor of psychometric g (-.59), whereas this was not true of the Hick g path coefficient. Thus, there is some initial indication that Hick g predicts psychometric g due to its shared variance with temporal g, whereas temporal g has independent predictive value.

Specifically, electronic word of mouth was a significant predictor of destination image (.91), and electronic word of mouth was significantly and positively associated with attitude toward destination (.90), and travel intention (.87). Further, destination image (.84) and attitude toward destination (.49) were significantly and positively associated with travel intention. Finally, destination image was positively and significantly related to attitude toward destination (.58).

As can be seen in the figure, gender was expected to influence physics motivation, strategy, and problem categorization. A focus on the deeper aspects of the material and problems, as indicated by categorizations, was expected to influence student achievement both directly, and indirectly, through the use of the more expert working-forward strategy. Consistent with the research, better problem categorization was expected to support better pictorial representations. With better pictorial representations, the use of the working-forward strategy was expected to increase as a deeper understanding of the concepts and principles and their relationship to one another increased. Finally, strategy use was expected to directly predict achievement with the working-forward strategy supporting higher achievement.

The findings illustrate that market-orientation has no direct influence on performance. However, this does not mean that market-orientation is not important for performance. Essentially, market-orientation has an indirect effect on performance via learning-orientation and innovativeness, as discussed later. The results demonstrate that innovativeness has a positive impact on performance in SMEs. Learning-orientation has a positive influence on innovativeness. The results indicate that learning-orientation mediates the relationship between market-orientation and innovativeness. The direct path between market-orientation and innovativeness was not significant, however, the paths between learning-orientation and innovativeness, and market-orientation and learning-orientation were significant, demonstrating the effect of market-orientation on innovativeness via learning-orientation. Market-orientation has a positive impact on learning-orientation in SMEs.

Racial discrimination had a significant direct effect on HIV-related stigma, depression and socialsupport. There was a significant indirect effect of racial discrimination on SRH via the mediator of HIV-related stigma. HIV-related stigma had a significant direct effect on depression, socialsupport, and SRH. Housing insecurity had significant direct effects on depression and social support.

Figure depicts the results of the inner model with the results of the bootstrapping, indicating that five of the six hypotheses were supported. In particular, perceived quality had a significant positive effect on perceived value, satisfaction, and loyalty (reg(std) =0.746, 0.373, and 0.142, respectively). Perceived value also had a significant positive effect on satisfaction (reg(std) = 0.389). Satisfaction had a significant positive effect on loyalty (reg(std) = 0.695). However, perceived value was found to have no significant effect on loyalty (reg(std) = 0.005). Perceived quality and satisfaction had the highest effects on loyalty, followed by perceived value.

Place attachment was found to positively influence both low and high PEB intentions of park visitors, as well as place satisfaction. Interestingly, while place satisfaction was found to exert a positive effect on low effort pro-environmental behavioural intentions, it negatively influenced high PEB intentions.

Intrinsic value was positively predicted by knowledge application (β = 0.12), the project‘s design features (β = 0.36), and pedagogical features (β = 0.45) of the service-learning subjects as experienced by the students. Similarly, self efficacy was positively affected by knowledge application (β = 0.15), the project's design features (β = 0.39), and pedagogical features (β = 0.27). These factors explained 42% of the variation of self-efficacy. However, the direct effect of the knowledge application was much less than the direct effect of the two dimensions of learning experiences. Students’ motivation had a positive direct effect on cognitive learning outcome. Knowledge application is positively predicted by their ratings on intrinsic value (β = 0.25) and self efficacy (β = 0.18) in completing the service learning subject. Students’ learning experience had a direct effect and an indirect effect mediated by motivation on their learning outcomes.

The model resulted in significant lagged, and positive effects of job resources TI on flow at work T2 (b = 0.26), as well as a positive effect of self-efficacy T1 on flow at work T2 (b = 0.41). Flow at work T1 – job resources T2 b = 0.33, flow at work T1-self-efficacy T2 b = 0.47.

The data provided support for the hypotheses to a large extent. Trust had a direct positive relationship on intentions to use with a standardized path coefficient of 0.60. A surprising result was that the direct path between perceived usefulness and intention to use was insignificant, as was the perceived ease of use effect on intention to use. Instead, the effect of context on perceived usefulness and perceived ease of use was found significant, with path coefficients of 0.56 and 0.77. As expected, perceived ease of use had a direct effect on perceived usefulness. Finally, no direct positive effect was found between personal initiative and character and intention to use.

The reliability of the single indicator latent variables was fixed at 99% for variables “children,” “price,” and “info, and 84% for “awcons.” All variables in the model have statistically significant coefficients. In terms of individual effects, attidaw have the strongest impact on awocons. Similar to attidaw and class, price has also a sizeable impact on awcons in the model. The lowest impact on awcons is that of children in the household, while access to info and reason have slightly higher effects. Attidaw significantly impact awcons in a positive relationship. Class has a significant positive impact on awcons in the model. We found a negative relationship between reason and awcons. Unexpectedly, children has a negative impact on the variable “info”. On the other hand, price significantly impacts awcons in a negative relationship.

For the model, the path coefficient from attitude toward chemistry to achievement is 0.19, which indicates a positive, though small, effect on achievement. The path between math ability and achievement is 0.49, which indicates a strong positive effect. The path coefficient between the third predictor, prior conceptual knowledge and achievement is 0.20, which again indicates a small positive effect of the conceptual knowledge on achievement.

The Project Environment variable construct is measured in the SEM model by the TC, SD and CE, and NT. The TC had the most influence in characterizing the Project Environment (coefficient: 0.70) followed by SD (coeffi cient: 0.48) and NT (coefficient: 0.40). CE had the least influence in characterizing the Project Environment (coefficient: -.38). The Organizational Characteristics variable construct is measured in the SEM model by the FN and the NW, CN and FN. The CN had the highest influence in characterizing Organizational Characteristics (coefficient: 0.91) followed by NW (coefficient: 0.82) and FN (coefficient: 0.55). CN had the least influence in characterizing Organizational Characteristics (coefficient: -.40). The Planning Efforts variable construct is measured in the SEM model by the PT, CM, and IA. The PT had the highest influence in characterizing Planning Efforts (coefficient: 0.54), followed by IA (coefficient: 0.51). PT had the least influence in characterizing Planning Efforts (coefficient: 0.42). The Project Planning Effectiveness variable construct is measured in the SEM model by the CV, TV, MV, and CS. TV had the highest influence in characterizing Project Planning Effectiveness (coefficient: -.72), followed by MV (coefficient: -.49) and CS (coefficient: 0.41). CV had the least influence in characterizing Project Planning Effectiveness (coefficient: -.34). The Project Environment was found to have a statistically significant direct influence on Planning Efforts (path coefficient: 0.72).

Among the three antecedents of breastfeeding intention, attitude was strongly associated with both subjective norms (r = 0.55) and perceived behavioral control (r = 0.56), but the magnitude of unattenuated ES between subjective norms and perceived behavioral control was relatively small (r = 0.39). Attitude, subjective norms, and PBC were all considerably associated with intention (r ≧ 0.50).

The strongest direct influence on Com was from sat (0.70). However, com was also influenced directly and positively by ach (0.37). T_EI had a significant positive effect on con(0.31). In addition, it had a negative effect on str(-0.54). Other notable paths included the positive effect of ach on con (0.61), the respectively positive and negative effects of con on sat (0.58) and str (-0.24), and the negative effect of str onsat (-0.44).

In the cross-validation data set, increased patient involvement is strongly associated with decreased decisional conflict (standardised regression coefficient Β = −.73). Both high involvement and low decisional conflict predict higher satisfaction with the physician (the associations were Β = .34 and -.28, respectively). The negative association of -.24 between the patients’ preference for involvement and experienced involvement. In considering possible confounders, a negative association of -.34 (p=<.001) was found between age and preference for involvement, suggesting that with increasing age, patients have a lower preference for involvement. Education and preference for involvement showed a weak positive association of .11 (p=.002), indicating that higher education is associated with a higher preference for involvement. Altogether, the interrelations between quality of life and the SDM-related constructs were relatively weak. The associations between physical and mental health-related quality of life and experienced involvement were -.01 (p=.876) and .04 (p=.545), respectively, and the association between mental quality of life and decisional conflict was -.16 (p=<.001).

Social media marketing activities had positive effects in value equity (β= .19), relationship equity (β= .36), and brand equity (β= .36). To restate, the entertainment, interaction, and word-of-mouth effects of Social media marketing activities work positively in enhancing customer equity drivers. Value equity and relationship equity had no significant effect on customer equity, while brand equity had a negative influence (β=−.45). The estimation results show that value equity (β= .47) and brand equity (β= .66) had positive effects on purchase intention. However, relationship equity did not have a significant influence on purchase intention. Purchase intention likely will improve by Social media marketing activities through value equity and brand equity. Finally, a path between purchase intention and customer equity was significant (β= .83). Since a path from purchase intention to customer equity is significant, Social media marketing activities of luxury fashion brands could consequently influence customer equity through the effects of value equity and brand equity on purchase intention.

Figure indicates that teachers’ feelings about school life correlate negatively to bureaucratic linkage (0.40) and positively to cultural linkage (0.86). School values in bureaucratic linkage and cultural linkage are themselves correlated with a coefficient of 0.39. It is evident that teachers’ feelings about school life regress negatively on bureaucratic linkage and positively on cultural linkage. It seems that cultural linkage has positive effects on teachers’ commitment, job satisfaction, sense of community, and order and discipline, whereas bureaucratic linkage has negative effects on all these aspects. Among others, job satisfaction is more vulnerable to the effects of school values in both bureaucratic linkage and cultural linkage.

According to the results of the statistical analysis, the latent exogenous variable of media had a positive direct effect on participants’ outdoor activities (Γ=0.27), attitudes toward sustainability (Γ=0.12), and behaviors pertaining to sustainability (Γ=0.18).  Regarding the interrelationships among endogenous variables, the results indicated that attitudes toward sustainability had a positive direct effect (β=0.67) on behaviors pertaining to sustainability. Similarly, participants’ tendency to engage in outdoor activities had a positive direct effect on behaviors (β=0.28). Furthermore, the results reflected positive direct effect of environmental values on behaviors pertaining to sustainability (β=0.15). It was also found that the effect of attitudes on participants’ tendency to engage in out door activities was statistically significant (β= 0.77). The significant effect of outdoor activities on environmental values (β= 0.18) showed that this endogenous variable could act as a mediator between attitudes and values. The latent exogenous variable of gender had a significant direct ef fect on attitudes toward sustainability. Furthermore, it was seen that the effect of gender on participants’ outdoor activities was significant(Γ=0.79).

Religion was significantly related to health indirectly via the pathway of increased forgiveness and reduced hostility. Participants who were more religious were significantly more likely to be forgiving (b = .59), and greater forgiveness was signifi cantly associated with less hostility (b = -.10). Finally, lower hostility was associated with greater subjective physical health (b = -.22).

Structural equation model results indicated a good fit between the model and data. Path tests showed a significant negative link between worker creative environment perceptions and intent to turnover. This finding is in support of theoretical expectations. The standardized path coefficient between these two variables was -0.77.

text: In summer, thermal comfort was determined to be directly affected by the thermal sensation of an individual (r = -0.344). Thermal sensation was operationalized by microclimatic conditions including perceived temperature (r = 0.561), perceived solar radiation level (r = 0.198), perceived wind speed (r = - 0.588) and perceived humidity level (r = 0.388), also by personal characteristics including age (r = 0.210), metabolic rate (r = 0.144) clothing value (r = 0.549), purpose of visit (r = 0.133) and thermal sensitivity (r = 0.187). In summer, people would feel less comfortable if they perceived strong solar radiation, high air temperature, low wind speed or high humidity (r = -0.344). In addition, thermal sensation of individuals was affected by their purpose of visit. People visiting a park for leisure purpose were more inclined to feel comfortable than those who came for work. Thermal comfort perceived by park visitors was found to be enhanced if they preceived a large amount of trees, water ponds or shade provisions to be present in parks (r = 0.142, 0.084 and 0.060). An individual’s thermal acceptability was shown to be influenced by the thermal comfort perceived (r = 0.637) and thermal sensation (r = -0.218). In addition, thermal acceptability could also be improved by having more trees, water ponds or shade provisions immediately visible in summer (r = 0.115, 0.088 and 0.042). Immediate visibility of trees were found to have a stronger impact than water ponds and in turn much stronger than shade provisions.

As shown in figure, six out of the ten hypotheses are accepted. They are vendor risk factors (VRF) to FP with a path coefficient of 0.68; CBF to vendor risk factors (VRF) with a path coefficient of 0.81; CBF to relationship risk factors (RRF) with a path coefficient of 0.79; vendor risk factors (VRF) to contract risk factors (CRF) with a path coefficient of 0.54; vendor risk factors (VRF) to relationship risk factors (RRF) with a path coefficient of 0.88; and contract risk factors (CRF) to relationship risk factors (RRF) with a path coefficient of 0.75. CBF to FP with a path coefficient of 0.28 is not supported, while relationship risk factors (RRF) to FP is not supported by the analysis as its path coefficient was 0.18. Additionally, CBF to contract risk factors (CRF) with a path coefficient of 0.13 is not supported. However, the path from contract risk factors (CRF) to FP with a path coefficient of 0.31 was found to be marginally significant.

The strongest predictor of environmental BEH was INT, followed by HAB. PBC had a weaker impact on BEH. While the relatively strong effects of INT and HAB strength were expected, the standardized regression weight of PBC on BEH is unexpectedly low, even if it was anticipated that the majority of the impact of PBC would be mediated by INT and PN. 36% of variation in behaviour was explained by the three variables, which is relatively low compared to models tested on a specific behaviour. INT are the first integrative variable, being influenced by ATT, PBC, PN and SN (in descending order of the magnitude of their impact). These four variables explain 55% of variation in intentions. Both the amount of explained variation and the strength of the impact of the variables fulfilled the expectations. The second integrative variable is PN, which is significantly predicted by SN, PBC, AC, AR, ST, SE (negative relation), and the NEP (in descending order of the magnitude of their impact). Together these seven variables explain 47% of variation in PN. There is not much variation in the impact the seven variables have on personal norms. AR should be more closely related to PN than for example general value orientations. HAB strength is related to INT, PN, and PBC as expected. The three variables explain 26% of variation in habit strength. The NEP is predicted positively by ST and negatively by SE. However, the strict causal chain leading from NEP via AC and AR to PN could not be confirmed.
What is characteristic here is the presence of only one positive connection between Media 2 and Emotional feelings.

Regarding the structural paths, contextual support positively predicted need satisfaction (b = .86), and in turn need satisfaction positively predicted motivation/self-determination (b = .15). Number of hits, the outcome variable, was directly predicted by contextual support (b = -.79) and need satisfaction (b = .97). However, motivation/self-determination did not yield a significant direct effect on the outcome variable.

Parenting style included two observed variables—authoritative and permissive style. Parenting style was significantly related with authoritative (β = .400) and permissive (β = .351). It shows that authoritative parenting style was the best predictor in this model. Attachment style also included two observed variables—secure and dismissive style. Attachment style was significantly related with secure (β = .587) and dismissive (β = .138). Self-regulation included two observed variables—impulse control and goal-setting. Self regulation was significantly related with impulse control (β = .369) and goal-setting (β = .375). Smartphone addiction included four observed variables—positive anticipation, withdrawal, cyberspace relationship and overuse. Smartphone addiction was significantly related with positive anticipation (β = .471), withdrawal (β = .182), cyberspace relationship (β = .517) and overuse (β = .510). For the relationship between latent variables, parenting style was positively significantly related with attachment style (β = .524). On the other hand, attachment style was positively related with self-regulation (β = .609). Furthermore, self-regulation was negatively related with smartphone addiction(β=-.308).

The latent variable, tax and social security payments, is constructed with seven indicators, which are based on official tax data and indicators concerning the impact of taxes. The highest loadings (correlations) are estimated for the broader indicators total tax revenue (0.95) as share of GDP and Tax and social security revenue (0.90) as share of GDP, whereas more specific indicators, such as total tax rate of profit (0.10), have less influence. Higher tax and social security payments increase the shadow economy (0.13) in the multivariate model. The latent variable, tax complexity and surveillance, is constructed with six indicators, which are based on specific cost of tax procedures and tax inspections. The highest loadings (correlations) are estimated for the indicators costs of compliance for importing and exporting (0.89) and number of tax payments per person (0.82), and for weaker indicators, such as tax staff per tax payers (0.42). The complexity and surveillance cannot be entirely separated because the complexity is often a result of enhanced surveillance. More tax complexity and surveillance reduces the shadow economy (−0.18). An explanation can be that complex tax systems offer more options to avoid paying taxes legally and hence reduce illegal activities per definition. The latent variable tax moral is constructed with two indicators bribe acceptable survey (0.95) and government benefits claimable survey (0.94). The tax moral shows no significant influence on the shadow economy (-0.01), but results should be regarded with care due to measuring problems. The R2 for the partial model Tax System is 0.73.

The results suggest that perceived usefulness, perceived ease of use, perceived playfulness, critical mass, and trust all exert positive and significant effects on intention to use SNS. Playfulness has the strongest effect on intention to use SNS (β = .45), followed in order by critical mass (β = .38), perceived ease of use (β = .15), trust (β = .15), and perceived usefulness (β = .11). In contrast to the direction hypothesized, though significant, normative pressure has a negative significant relationship with intention to use SNS (β = -.08). As expected, the actual use is found to be positively related to intention to use. Finally, contrary to our expectation, a direct link between perceived playfulness and actual usage is found to be significant (β = .15).

There was a relationship between EO and CM. It was concluded that this relationship exists and is positive, as these results exhibited a standardized factor loading of 0.680. There was a relationship between CM and BP in the context of retail firms doing business in the supermarket industry of Santa Catarina. This hypothesis was also confirmed, corroborating the results of earlier studies that had demonstrated a positive relationship between CM and BP. It is also noteworthy that the relationship was confirmed by a positive standardized factor loading of 0.72. This result enabled another of the objectives to be achieved: identification of a relationship between CM and BP. There was a relationship between EO and BP. It can be concluded that this hypothesis was also confirmed, corroborating the results of a considerable proportion of previous studies of EO and BP, as the relationship was shown to be positive. This hypothesis was confirmed with a standardized factor loading of 0.513, achieving another part of the objective, which was to identify a relationship between EO and CM.

The hypothesized relationships between technological strategy and innovation performance constructs, as mediated by the intensity (here measured both in terms of　partner and phase collaboration) are supported by the data. Standard regression weights are 0.59 (significant at the 0.001 level) between technological strategy and partner intensity constructs and 0.47 (significant at the 0.001 level) between partner intensity and innovation performance. In the case of phases intensity their measures are 0.41 (significant at the 0.001 level) and 0.19 (significant at the 0.01 level), respectively. Concerning the construct openness variety, instead, its central role on the final impact on innovation performance is evident. Regression weight is 0.27 (significant at the 0.01 level). The negative impact is, in turn, influenced by the constructs partner intensity and phase intensity. The first positively impacts on openness variety: measured regression weight is 0.40 (significant at the 0.001 level). The second pattern, on the contrary, reveals a negative impact: regression weight is 0.29 (significant at the 0.001 level).

The positive path coefficient between ecological motives and attitude was quite strong and significant, while the path between political motives and attitude was significant but weaker. The religious motives were even lesser related to attitudes, as expected. The path between attitude and intention was significant and positive, as expected.

The assumptions referring to the acceptance construct conceptualised on the basis of the Theory of Reasoned action are confirmed. The Aact strongly determines the BI to use mobile marketing services. Likewise the BI is positively influenced by SN. However, this relationship appears rather weak. The model generated also suggests that the Aact is strongly influenced by SN. This implies that for SN have only a slight direct influence on the BI, but that they determine it indirectly by influencing Aact. "IN" influences "EK" positively, and the "IS" construct determines "ATA". "EK" again effects the "Aact" positively. The magnitude of this relationship is, however, very low. The hypothesis can thus be claimed as being confirmed, but the deduction of any further implications is not really possible. This is also true for the relationship between the constructs "ATA" and "Aact". Additionally, the positive relationship between "PU" and "Aact" is confirmed as well as the positive influence of PUinf, PUent, and PUsoc on overall utility. Confirmation can also be found for the negative influence of "PR" on the Aact.

Using structural equation modeling, we found that depression influenced not only the HRQoL psychological, but also the HRQoL physical domain, whereas severity of heart failure, as measured by NYHA functional class, affected the HRQoL physical, but not the HRQoL psychological domain.
It can be concluded from figure that the most important and effective sub-dimension of the static complexity is Y10.

Age was not related to other demographic variables but to employment outcome. The association between good employment outcome and gender was indirect, operating through the association between education and employment outcome. Pre-injury psychiatric disorders were related to employment outcome through their relationship with pre-injury employment status and by being associated with reported mood changes. Lower education resulted in follow-up unemployment both directly as well as indirectly via its relationships with pre-injury unemployment and with behavioural changes. Similarly, longer PTA duration affected employment outcome both directly as well as indirectly, by its association with behavioural and cognitive changes. Spinal injuries were related to employment outcome indirectly through its association with mood changes. Limb injuries affected employment outcome directly.

SEM Model I was composed of six direct and two indirect pathways through four latent variables. The four latent variables all exhibited negative direct effects on the soil burdens of SVBPs, and the effect coefficients increased in magnitude in the order of 0.048 (soil characteristics) < 0.083 (climate conditions) < 0.126 (topographic conditions) < 0.572 (compounds properties). In addition, topographic conditions posed impacts on the climate conditions and soil characteristics, which led to the two indirect effect pathways. Despite the large chemical diversities of compounds, the pesticides with low VP and high LogKOW values were found to readily accumulate in soils. Moreover, compounds properties displayed the negative direct effect (−0.572) on the soil burdens of SVBPs. Namely, the compounds with high VP and low LogKOW are usually poorly concentrated in soils. The topographic conditions indicated by elevation and slope, posed notable negative effects on the soil burdens of SVBPs, relative to climate conditions and soil characteristics. The two climate factors, MAP and MAT, had effect on the soil burdens of SVBPs. The sand and SOC, two representatives of soil characteristics, had effect on the soil burdens of SVBPs, as the two soil characteristics were negatively correlated. The soil burdens of SVBPs are dependent on soil characteristics, topographic conditions of soil , compounds properties and/or their interaction effects. By comparison, soil characteristics (including SOC) pose minor influences on the soil burdens of SVBPs, compared to both topographic and climate conditions of soil sites.

All paths are significant. As expected, ICT-related schl shows a substantial positive effect on tchr (β = 0.53). Tchr, in turn, has a strong impact on ICT use (β = 0.40). Next to this indirect effect of ICT-related schl, there is also a smaller direct effect on use in teaching (β = 0.26).

Figure shows the graphical description of the results of path coefficients. Attitude (b = 0.431), subjective norm (b = 0.158), and perceived behavioral control (b = 0.501), significantly impact intention to use m-learning. However, perceived behavioral control has the highest impact followed by attitude and subjective norm. Perceived ease of use and perceived usefulness were found to significantly relate to attitude with 0.486 and 0.491, respectively. Concerning normative beliefs, instructor readiness significantly influenced subjective norm (b = 0.579), but student readiness did not influence subjective norm. Finally, for control beliefs, both perceived self-efficacy and learning autonomy were significantly related to perceived behavior control with 0.639 and 0.243, respectively.

The significant direct pathways were found from HL to QOL, and SE played a partial mediating role between HL and QOL in the CHD population (see details in Fig. 2). HL significantly indirectly affected QOL through SE. The direct effect of HL on SE was − 0.32, the direct effect of SE on QOL was 0.65, the direct effect of HL on QOL was − 0.27, the indirect effect of HL on QOL was − 0.21 (− 0.32*0.65), and the total effect of HL on QOL was − 0.48 (− 0.27–0.21). Therefore, the total effect was greater than the direct effect, the direct effect was greater than the indirect effect of HL on QOL, and SE only played a partial mediating role.

According toFigure 2, CK and PK are both significant positive predictors in explaining the variationof the TPACK knowledge (path coefficients = .19 and .61, respectively) while Web 2.0-related TK and PK are the significantly positive predictors of TPK (path coefficients =.14 and .52, respectively). The cyberwellness factor is also a statistically positivepredictor to TPK and TPACK constructs (path coefficients = .13 and .15, respectively, p< .01).

On the other hand, results indicate that dimensional comparisons between the SC affect CS. This is indicated by significant negative coefficients for the paths from SC_CH to CS_BIO, and from SC_BIO to CS_CH. Moreover, all paths from the AC variables to the respective SC, and from SC to the respective CS were significant. The correlation between AC_CH and AC_BIO was higher than the correlation between the respective self-concept variables.

The standardized regression coefficients are also included in figure. These show that all relationships are in the expected directions, with performance on different cognitive measures correlating positively with each other, and age and MD correlating negatively with cognitive performance. The correlation between the two executive function measures is positive, but moderate. The strongest relationships are between age and MD, with MD increasing (reflecting a decrease in white matter integrity) as age increases; and age and speed, with speed declining in aging.

Fig. 3 shows that patient satisfaction with new complete dentures was powerfully related to accuracy of reproduction of jaw relationship and to a lesser extent to patient adaptability factors. In turn accuracy of reproduction of retruded jaw relation was powerfully influenced by the security of the mandibular dentures and to the quality of the mandibular residual alveolar ridge.

The positive relationships between the visual quality and the pleasantness of the soundscape were statistically significant. Traffic noise is the most critical factor among the sound sources affecting the pleasantness of sounds and visual quality as illustrated. In addition, the harmony of environments was significantly affected by the pleasantness of the soundscape.

All coefficients and correlations were again estimated using the full model with all determinants. The latent variable labor market regulations depends mainly on the three indicators costs of workers dismissal (0.71), a labor freedom index (0.61) by Heritage Foundation and centralized collective bargaining (−0.54). All indicators are scaled so that higher numbers mean more freedom and less regulation. The fourth indicator hiring and firing practices (−0.01) is nearly uncorrelated with the labor market regulations and has no connection to the shadow economy. Higher costs of worker dismissal lead to more shadow economy, while more centralized collective bargaining leads to less shadow economy. These two indicators are nearly uncorrelated (0.09), demonstrating that the concept of labor market regulations is not one-dimensional. Using more than one indicator is absolutely necessary at this point to avoid misleading conclusion. The remaining latent variables unemployment (0.00), participation rights (−0.06) and labor wages (0.03) have no significant influence on the shadow economy ceteris paribus.

Illness perceptions had a significant direct influence on depression (0.72), anxiety (0.55) and family functioning (−0.17). Several significant indirect (mediating) pathways were identified: sexual problems mediated the relationship between depression and sexual satisfaction, while sexual satisfaction mediated the relationship between sexual problems and marital functioning. In turn marital functioning mediated the relationship between sexual satisfaction and family functioning. Sexual satisfaction was also found to be influenced by anxiety through the mediation of BISCS during intimacy. Of the demographic variables, only gender was maintained in the final model due to its direct influence on both sexual problems and sexual satisfaction.

Among the nine paths of the modified model, five paths were significant. The direct paths from attachment avoidance to smartphone addiction (ß = –.37) and attachment avoidance to loneliness (ß = .46) were statistically significant. The direct path from attachment anxiety to loneliness (ß = .55) was significant, and the paths from loneliness to depression (ß = .54) and from depression to smartphone addiction (ß = .34) were also valid. The result of bootstrapping on the mediating effect between attachment avoidance and depression was significant, and the mediating effect between attachment anxiety and depression was also significant.

Based on these results, as shown in model, quality has a positive influence on satisfaction. Additionally, model shows that process also influences satisfaction positively. However, model reveals that information influences satisfaction negatively. In other words, as more information is provided to inpatients less satisfied they become. We also note that the three hypotheses related to status, quality, process and information are all negative and significant; while status influences satisfaction positively. As a result, all seven research hypotheses are supported as the relevant paths are statistically significant.

Among females stress management did not indicate a direct relation with depression. Another important result is the negative relationship between physical activity and BMI, which translates into "more physical activity – less weight problems". Model also indicated that stress management had a direct relation with depression. The high score on the stress management means less ability to handle stress, indicating that individuals with reduced ability to handle stress suffer more from depression.

At community level, increasing women justified IPVAW was positively associated with sexual abuse (b= 1.395) and emotional abuse (b= 0.607), but not physical abuse. Increasing man justified IPVAW in the community was positively associated only spousal physical abuse (b= 1.385), but not sexual abuse and emotional abuse. Similarly, increasing women who had witnessed IPVAW in the community was positively associated only spousal physical abuse (b= 0.703), but not sexual and emotional abuse. There was positive correlation between all three types of IPVAW at community-level (physical vs. emotional [b = 0.485]; physical vs. sexual [b = 0.659]; and sexual vs. emotional [b = 0.579]). In addition, there was positive correlation between woman and man justified IPVAW at community level (b = 0.010), such that women with tolerant attitudes were more likely to have husbands with tolerant attitudes too. However, community-level correlations between woman and man justified IPVAW were relatively less pronounced.

As expected, urgency and lack of perseverance correlated moderately with each other (r = 0.32, P < 0.001) and predicted the use of aggressive suppression (R2 = 0.07) and worry (R2 = 0.16) at bedtime. In turn, urgency and lack of perseverance, which correlated with each other independently of impulsivity (r = 0.20, P < 0.001), predicted sleep problems (R2 = 0.14). Thus, the use of aggressive suppression and worry to counter unwanted intrusive thoughts at bedtime mediated the effects of urgency and lack of perseverance on sleep problems. The effects of urgency and lack of perseverance on insomnia were almost completely mediated by the use of aggressive suppression and worry.

In the final model, results showed that hours worked each day, years of education, and social resources had significant negative relationships with abuse behavior while stress level showed a significant and positive relationship with abuse behavior. Hours worked each day showed a negative relationship with abuse behavior implying that the more hours of work each day by the caregiver, the less psychological abusive behavior they manifested. Conversely, caregivers with more years of education, lower social resources, and higher work stress were more likely to demonstrate psychological abuse behavior.

The larger the path coefficient, the more important the attrib utes or factors can be considered as an indicator of the success. Accordingly, TMC emerges as the most CSF with a path coefficient of 0.853. The success factors have a significant positive impact on the success of the construction organization, is found to be supported because the path coefficient (0.99) is significant at a 0.05 significance level. The TMC is the most CSF with a path coefficient of 0.853. This factor consists of the following attributes: (1) an effective risk management capability in the organization (TMC1), (2) professionalism/culture in the organization (TMC2), (3) competitive strategy used by the organization (TMC3), and (4) financial soundness of the organization in terms of better liquidity and working capital (TMC4). Because these attributes are directly governed by the top management, the name is top management competence. The EP is the second most important success factor with a path coefficient of 0.78. The attributes under this factor are (1) client’s satisfaction in terms of product and services (EP1) and (2) customer satisfaction in terms of product and services (EP2), (3) the company’s reputation/track record (EP3), and (4) experience in the construction business (EP4). EP is highly significant for the success of organizations. The CCM received a path coefficient of 0.71 and was placed at the third position. The attributes under this factor are (1) availability of cost control measures in the organization (CCM1) and (2) favorable government policies (CCM2). The lowest possible overall cost in the organization can be achieved only when the cost control measures taken by the organization are effectively keeping in view the objectives of the owner’s investment. The RES was placed at the fourth position with a path coefficient of 0.68. The attributes under this factor are (1) the availability of qualified staff in the organization (RES1) and (2) the availability of equipment, material, and labor as per requirement of the project (RES2). Availability of qualified staff in the organization is the key to its success in a competitive market. The SCL was placed at the last position with a very low path coefficient of 0.51. The attributes under this factor are (1) efficient supply chain management (SCL1) and (2) availability of dynamic leadership (SCL2). Supply chain management has a strong correlation with project success.

For female students, we found that interactivity of the user interface is important to determine sociability (β = 0.29) and utilitarian (β = 0.30), but not hedonic (β = 0.13). Also, we found that social presence is important to determine sociability (β = 0.43), utilitarian (β = 0.34) and hedonic (β = 0.43). In order to determine compulsive use, we found only hedonic (β = 0.40) to have a significant and positive relationship with compulsive use. Sociability (β = –0.01) and utilitarian (β = –0.03) had no significant impact on compulsive use. Finally, compulsive use did impact academic performance (β = 0.47), physical performance (β = 0.65) and social performance (β = 0.57) of female students.

Considering the exploratory nature of this study, assessment of the structural equation model showed R2 values that are reasonable. The structural equation model explained 53% of the variance in alummi loyalty, 23% of the variance in absorption, 30% of the variance in dedication, and 20% of the variance in vigor. Within the sample, trust in benevolence had a statistically signifcant association with all student engagement sub-dimensions, that is, vigor, dedication, and absorption. Trust in honesty also had a statistically signifcant association with student engagement’s absorption and vigor, but not with dedication. Afective commitment had a statistically signifcant efect on all student engagement dimensions, that is, vigor, dedication, and absorption. Afective confict did not have a statistically signifcant association with any student engagement dimensions. Last, satisfaction had a statistically signifcant association with student engagement’s dimension of vigor. However, no statistically signifcant association was found with student engagement’s dimensions of absorption and dedication. Further examination of the structural model indicated that absorption and vigor did not have a statistically signifcant association with alumni loyalty, in contrast to dedication, which did have a statistically signifcant association with alumni loyalty. Figure shows the path model diagram including statistically signifcant path loadings and signifcance levels.

Regarding the structural paths, contextual support positively predicted need satisfaction (b = .85), and in turn need satisfaction positively predicted motivation/self-determination (b = .15). Unexpectedly, none of the predictive variables (contextual support, need satisfaction, and motivation/self-determination) directly predicted participants’ final grade.

The edges between the dimensions in figure represent direct relationships. The indirect effect of one dimension on another is equal to the product of the regression coefficients of the two directly connected dimensions. For job satisfaction, the standardized factor loadings ranged from 0.51 (job_reward_satisfaction) to 0.90 (org_man_satisfaction), and for occupational burnout, the values ranged from 0.34 (redu_per_accomplish) to 0.71 (emotional exhaustion). There was a direct effect of job satisfaction on occup_burnout (−0.52) and turnover intention (−0.29), a direct effect of occup_burnout on turnover intention (0.28), and also an indirect effect of job satisfaction on turnover intention through burnout as a mediator. For turnover intention, job satisfaction had smaller indirect effect than its direct effect.

The research study indicates that Facilitating Conditions, Performance Expectancy, and Social Influence would help enhance the behavioral intention to adapt E-learning system. It has also been observed that a positive influence was subjected upon use behavioral intention including the behavioral and facilitating conditions. Positive influence was also subjected upon the Performance Expectancy and Social Influence on Behavioral Intention. With the help of this outcome, it is possible to indicate the E-learning significance in terms of competency and high confidence levels when making use of online learning platforms.

Perception of Mall explained 28 and 36 percent of the total variance of Brand Affect and Brand Trust, respectively, while the latter two endogenous constructs explained 87 percent total variance of Patronage Loyalty. This model is considered proficient particularly in the estimation of Patronage Loyalty, where Brand Trust and Brand Affect explained the former almost entirely. All associations amongst the latent constructs in the overall structural model were significant except for the association between Perception of Mall and Brand Trust. Although insignificant, there was evidence to suggest that Perception of Mall can improve Patronage Loyalty via the indirect effect of Brand Trust. This indirect effect was also imminently enhanced with the significant semi-partial correlation between Brand Trust and Brand Affect. The rest of the associations were positive and the strength of these associations was considerable. The results also confirmed that Brand Trust and Brand Affect were correlated (0.62). Therefore, there was a semi-partial effect of these two constructs on Patronage Loyalty. In short, both constructs, i.e. Brand Trust and Brand Affect, had internal consistency.

The structural model indicates that there is a significant, inverse and moderate relationship between reported dissonance and attitude. The implication is that as the level of reported dissonance increases, the motivation to change one’s attitude in favour of the purchased brand decreases. Furthermore, there is a significant, inverse and moderate relationship between reported dissonance and trivialisation. In addition, reported dissonance and justification are significantly and inversely related with moderate strength. The implication is that as reported dissonance increases, the motivation to justify the incorrect choice and not having made another selection decreases. However, the structural model indicates that there is no significant relationship between reported dissonance and selective exposure.

Edu was also significantly associated with DSY. The greatest contribution to PI came from Mn-A. NBT was negatively associated with age, PI, Mn-B, and Mn-A, in decreasing order.

Results revealed that all hypotheses are supported. Curiosity about other people was found to exert a direct effect on perceived ease of use. In addition, subjective norm, curiosity, and perceived ease of use all exerted direct effects on perceived enjoyment. Of the three antecedents that affected perceived enjoyment, perceived ease of use exerts the strongest direct effect, while curiosity exerted the strongest total effect (due to the indirect effect between curiosity and perceived enjoyment, as mediated via perceived ease of use). Of the four paths that were examined in the structural models, only three were statistically significant – the exception being perceived usefulness. In contrast, the other three paths leading to usage were all ignificant: subjective norm, perceived enjoyment, and perceived ease of use. Of the three antecedents that affect usage, subjective norm was found to exert the strongest direct and total effect. In addition, perceived enjoyment exerted the second strongest direct effect, while also peceived ease of use exerts a strong total effect (both directly and also indirectly, as mediated by perceived enjoyment).

Dispositional mindfulness was found to have a positive, direct effect on both self-concept clarity (B = 0.53) and psychological well-being (B = 0.25). Self-concept clarity demonstrated a direct relationship with psychological well-being (B = 0.34) and was also found to partially mediate the relationship between dispositional mindfulness and self-concept clarity. A significant indirect effect of Dispositional mindfulness on psychological well-being via self-concept clarity was observed (B = 0.25).

The SEM-analyzed data provide evidence that the three dimensions of an entrepreneur’s resilience (hardiness, optimism, and resourcefulness) have direct and positive impacts on creative performance, but with different effect sizes. Resilience resourcefulness was found to have the highest impact size (0.26) on creative performance, followed by resilience optimism (0.24) and resilience hardiness (0.23). More specifically, the path from resilience hardiness to institutional orientation (0.46) and the path from institutional orientation to creative performance (0.56) were found to be significant with positive signs, thus supporting the effect of institutional orientation in the relationship between resilience hardiness and creative performance. Similarly, the impact of resilience resourcefulness on institutional orientation (0.41) and the impact of institutional orientation on creative performance (0.56) were found to be significant with positive signs, thus supporting institutional orientation in the relationship between resilience resourcefulness and creative performance. Finally, the effect of resilience optimism on institutional orientation (0.44) and the effect of institutional orientation on creative performance (0.56) were found to be significant and positive, thus supporting the effect of institutional orientation in the relationship between resilience optimism and creative performance.

Feel perception induces positive emotional value. Think perception induces positive emotional value. Think perception induces positive functional value. Service quality induces positive emotional value. Service quality induces positive functional value. Emotional value induces positive customer satisfaction. Functional value induces positive customer satisfaction. From the results of hypothesis testing, several paths of this model were supported: feel perception affects customer satisfaction by means of emotional value; service quality affects customer satisfaction by means of functional and emotional values; and think perception affects customer satisfaction through emotional and functional values. The results also showed that think perception and service quality have stronger effects than sense perception and feel perception because of the larger coefficients of think perception and service quality in the model. In addition, the results demonstrated that think perception and service quality are very important factors when a company attempts to implement experiential marketing.

This study explains the fundamental argument that internet banking adoption intentions are highly influenced by respondents’ attitude toward internet banking, and these attitudes are influenced by perceived usefulness and perceived ease of use. The latter two are the fundamental TAM constructs of internet banking services which are further affected by social influence, internet banking awareness, quality of internet connections and computer self-efficacy. The quality of internet connection is still a major issue in many developing countries like India. As a result of this study, social influence emerged as a major determinant ( 0.50) of the attitude toward online banking. The value 0.50 reflects that friends and relatives play a significant role in motivating customers to use online banking. It is also observed that respondents rarely receive information about online banking from banks, and therefore, the coefficient of internet banking awareness is low (0.32). Thus, low internet banking awareness is an important factor that may result in a lower rate of internet banking adoption. The effect of demographic details on attitude toward online banking is not statistically significant. The value of R2 for perceived ease of use is 0.376. That is, 37.6 per cent of variance is explained by the two factors quality of internet connection and computer self-efficacy.

The model tests show convincing support for a strong relationship between employee creative environment perceptions and willingness to leave. In other words, worker perceptions of the creative environment will be significantly related to turnover intentions. Stated in terms of the research model, workers who have creativity support, creativity work characteristics, and a low to zero presence of creativity blocks, will be more likely to stay and less likely to leave. Furthermore, model evaluation strongly suggests that these findings are relevant for non-creative professional employees.

Figure shows that the Cronbach’s alpha coefficients of reliability of the variables intended for their respective SPO constructs ranged from acceptable to good: structure (0.790), process (0.702), and outcome (0.600), an indication that the variables were a reliable measure of their intended constructs. Figure 4 also shows the remaining nine variables that reflected their intended SPO constructs in the structural equation model. These were three structure-related dimensions: availability of equipment (S1), supply of critical medicines (S2) and accessibility of chronic disease care (S4); three process-related dimensions: attending to patients’ health needs (P2), professional conduct of the nurses (P3) and friendliness of the nurses (P4); and three outcome-related dimensions: coherence of integrated chronic disease care (O1), patient confidence in the nurses (O3), and competence of the nurses (O5). Findings from the mediation path model showed that three structure-related dimensions of care (availability of equipment; supply of critical medicines; and accessibility of chronic disease care) correlated directly with three outcome-related dimensions of care (coherence of integrated chronic disease care; and competence of the nurses and patient confidence in the nurses) and three process-related dimensions of care (nurses’ friendliness with patients; professional conduct of the nurses; and attendance of the nurses to patients’ health needs). Independent of structure, good process correlated with good outcome, an indication that good process mediated the relationship between good structure and good outcome.

The structural models reflect multi-regression analysis and path analysis that model the relationships between the latent variables by outlining the explained and unexplained variance. Sign, size, and statistical significance of the path coefficients represent the strength of relationships among the constructs. The hypothesized relationships as shown in figure, and based on path coefficients are positive and significant. As shown in the models, procurement system would have a positive effect on information cost is supported. Information cost is significantly influenced by procurement system at β = 0.19. However, information cost fully mediates the relationship between procurement system and transaction cost. Procurement system has a substantial effect on project procurement cost at β = 0.13. Project procurement cost is fully mediated the relationship between procurement system and transaction cost. Procurement system has a significant effect on contract administration cost at β = 0.1. Administration cost mediates the relationship between procurement system and transaction cost. Procurement system significantly influence the contract enforcement cost at β = 0.1. Enforcement cost mediates the relationship between procurement system and transaction cost.
